{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:29:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:29:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17895"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17895"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.34,0.1,0.14,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114649"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96652"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114649"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is admitted to the hospital and is currently fasting. He has a history of type 1 diabetes mellitus and is insulin deficient. Due to the lack of insulin, his body is undergoing ketogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the rate-limiting enzyme of ketogenesis that is being stimulated by fasting and insulin deficiency?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thiolase","HMG-CoA synthase","HMG-CoA lyase","Hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase","Acetyl-CoA carboxylase"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHMG-CoA synthase\u003C/strong\u003E is the rate-limiting enzyme in ketogenesis, which is the process by which ketone bodies are produced in the liver. This enzyme catalyses the conversion of acetoacetyl-CoA to HMG-CoA, a crucial step in the production of ketone bodies. During fasting or insulin deficiency, such as in this patient with type 1 diabetes, the body increases fatty acid oxidation, leading to the production of acetyl-CoA, which is then converted to ketone bodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiolase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the initial step of ketogenesis, converting two molecules of acetyl-CoA into acetoacetyl-CoA, but it is not the rate-limiting step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHMG-CoA lyase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the conversion of HMG-CoA to acetoacetate, a ketone body, but it is not the rate-limiting enzyme.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the interconversion of acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate, two types of ketone bodies, but it is not the rate-limiting step in ketogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetyl-CoA carboxylase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in fatty acid synthesis, not ketogenesis, and is not relevant to the process described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["HMG-CoA synthase is the rate-limiting enzyme in the process of ketogenesis.","Ketogenesis occurs in the liver during periods of fasting or insulin deficiency.","Insulin deficiency leads to increased fatty acid oxidation and ketone body production."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a glance. 4th ed. Chichester: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020;64(4):607-47.","Wang Y, Wu R. The effect of fasting on human metabolism and psychological health. Dis Markers. 2022;2022:5653739.","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, glucose metabolism. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 [updated 2023 Jul 17].","Chandel NS. Lipid metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021;13(9):a040576."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96652"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17895"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96652"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T14:38:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T14:39:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10609"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114649"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela